The problem here is in your `similarColumns` method.  In it, you are only comparing one column with the value from the other column.  In the case of your first example, Each value from column 2 `{5,2,9,5,4}` exists only once in column 1 `{5,7,4,9,2}`.  Even though 5 appears twice in column 2, it only appears once in column 1.  Therefore, the conditional `!= 1` passes for both instances of 5 in column 2.

You can fix this easily enough by extending your code to repeat the check in the opposite direction
```java
public static boolean similarColumns(int[][] similar, int col1, int col2) {
  boolean isSimilar = true;
  for (int[] ints : similar) {
    if (numInColumn(similar, col1, ints[col2]) != 1 &amp;&amp; numInColumn(similar, col2, ints[col1]) != 1) {
      isSimilar = false;
      break;
    }
  }
  return isSimilar;
}
```

If you are able to use non-primitive Objects and types, you can also accomplish this fairly easily without loops using the Java8 Stream api.  I&#39;d recommend rotating your columns to rows to make it a bit easier as well.  Something like this:
```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
  int[][] my2dArray = new int[][]{
    {4, 5, 4, 7},
    {3, 7, 3, 2},
    {2, 4, 2, 9},
    {2, 9, 2, 5},
    {1, 2, 1, 4}};

  /* creates new array
    {4, 3, 2, 2, 1},
    {5, 7, 4, 9, 2},
    {4, 3, 2, 2, 1},
    {7, 2, 9, 5, 4},
   */
  int[][] rotatedArray = new int[my2dArray[0].length][my2dArray.length];

  rotate(my2dArray, rotatedArray);

  for (int i = 0; i &lt; rotatedArray.length; i++) {
    for (int j = i + 1; j &lt; rotatedArray.length; j++) {
      System.out.println(&quot;Column &quot; + i + &quot; is similar to Column &quot; + j + &quot;: &quot; + similarColumns(rotatedArray[i], rotatedArray[j]));
    }
  }
}

private static boolean similarColumns(int[] column1, int[] column2) {

  // creates a sorted array of distinct values
  int[] filteredColumn1 = Arrays.stream(column1).distinct().sorted().toArray();
  int[] filteredColumn2 = Arrays.stream(column2).distinct().sorted().toArray();

  // if the length changed, then the column contained duplicate values
  boolean lengthUnchanged = filteredColumn1.length == column1.length &amp;&amp; filteredColumn2.length == column2.length;

  return Arrays.equals(filteredColumn1, filteredColumn2) &amp;&amp; lengthUnchanged;
}

private static void rotate(int[][] oldArray, int[][] rotatedArray) {
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; oldArray[0].length; i++) {
    for (int j = oldArray.length - 1; j &gt;= 0; j--) {
      rotatedArray[i][j] = oldArray[j][i];
    }
  }
}
```
Another way to remove duplicate values would be to assign the array to a `HashSet`.  A `HashSet` can only contain unique values, so something like:
```java
int[] filteredColumn1 = new HashSet&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(IntStream.of(column1).boxed().toArray(Integer[]::new))).stream().mapToInt(i -&gt; i).sorted.toArray();
```
would also work, although it may be a bit overly complicated.

